<paragraph blockId="28.[360,548,1172,1230]" box="[360,548,1172,1198]" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">
<taxonomicName box="[360,478,1172,1198]" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Pterosauria</taxonomicName>
indet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="709" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[360,548,1172,1230]" box="[385,521,1204,1230]" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">
(
<figureCitation box="[394,469,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="27.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@27.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIG. 20. — Pterosaur teeth from Angeac-Charente:A, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-24) in labial view;B, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-10) in lingual view; C, D, Pterodactyloidea indet. A, (ANG M-42) in lingual (C) and mesial (D) views; E, F, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-43) in lingual (E) and mesial (F) views; G, H, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-112) in lingual (G) and mesial (H) views; I, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-40) in lingual view; J, K, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-41) in labial (J) and distal (K) views; L, M, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-113) in lingual (L) and mesial (M) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902083/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
J-M)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[130,777,1268,1613]" box="[132,270,1268,1294]" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[130,777,1268,1613]" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">
A third morphological group of pterosaurian teeth corresponds to slender, recurved crowns that are characterized by a subcircular cross section and poorly distinct carinae (
<figureCitation box="[531,599,1363,1389]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="27.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-23@27.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIG. 20. — Pterosaur teeth from Angeac-Charente:A, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-24) in labial view;B, Pterodactyloidea indet.A (ANG M-10) in lingual view; C, D, Pterodactyloidea indet. A, (ANG M-42) in lingual (C) and mesial (D) views; E, F, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-43) in lingual (E) and mesial (F) views; G, H, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-112) in lingual (G) and mesial (H) views; I, Pterodactyloidea indet. B, (ANG M-40) in lingual view; J, K, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-41) in labial (J) and distal (K) views; L, M, Pterosauria indet. (ANG M-113) in lingual (L) and mesial (M) views. Scale bar: 500 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902083/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Fig.20</figureCitation>
J-M).The enamel is smooth whereas the basal part of the crown devoid of enamel (i.e., basal portion of labial and lingual faces) shows an irregular rugose texture.Teeth of this morphology can be observed in some non-pterodactyloid taxa(e.g.,the Late Jurassic rhamphorhynchid genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hone, Tischlinger, Frey &amp; Röper" authorityYear="2012" box="[198,330,1523,1549]" class="Reptilia" family="Rhamphorhynchidae" genus="Bellubrunnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[198,330,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">Bellubrunnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hone" box="[344,518,1523,1549]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hone" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="39312" refId="ref41379" refString="HONE D. W. E., TISCHLINGER H., FREY E. &amp; ROPER M. 2012. - A new non-pterodactyloid pterosaur from the Late Jurassic of southern Germany. PLoS ONE 7 (7): e 39312. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0039312" type="journal article" year="2012">
Hone 
<emphasis box="[410,459,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) and archaeopterodactyloids (e.g., ctenochasmatids; 
<bibRefCitation author="Perea" box="[434,607,1554,1581]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Perea" pageId="28" pageNumber="709" pagination="298 - 306" refId="ref45487" refString="PEREA D., SOTO M., TORINO P., MESA V. &amp; MAISEY J. G. 2018. - A Late Jurassic -? earliest Cretaceous ctenochasmatid (Pterosauria, Pterodactyloidea): The first report of pterosaurs from Uruguay. Journal of South American Earth Sciences 85: 298 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jsames. 2018.05.011" type="journal article" year="2018">
Perea 
<emphasis box="[495,546,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="709">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
); therefore, this third morphotype cannot be identified beyond Pterosauria indet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
